<main class="content">

  <p>When a will is contested in court, the average legal cost is $35,000 — and that's just the average. Complex disputes can easily exceed $100,000, with costs often paid from the estate itself, reducing what beneficiaries ultimately receive.</p>

  <h2>Why Are Will Disputes So Expensive?</h2>

  <p>Will contests involve:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Solicitor fees</strong> — Both sides need legal representation</li>
    <li><strong>Barrister fees</strong> — Court appearances require barristers</li>
    <li><strong>Expert witnesses</strong> — Medical experts to assess capacity, valuers for assets</li>
    <li><strong>Court filing fees</strong> — Multiple applications and hearings</li>
    <li><strong>Mediation costs</strong> — Often required before trial</li>
    <li><strong>Time</strong> — Cases can take 1-3 years to resolve</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Who Pays?</h2>

  <p>In many cases, legal costs come out of the estate — meaning everyone loses. Even the "winner" of a will dispute often receives less than they would have if there had been no dispute at all.</p>

  <p>In some cases, the losing party is ordered to pay costs. This can be financially devastating for someone who challenged a will and lost.</p>

  <div class="cta-box">
    <h3>The Hidden Cost</h3>
    <p>Beyond money, will disputes destroy families. Siblings who go to court rarely speak again. The emotional toll — stress, anger, grief complicated by conflict — lasts far longer than the legal battle.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>What Causes Will Disputes?</h2>

  <p>Most contested wills share common factors:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Unequal distribution</strong> — One child receives more than others</li>
    <li><strong>Excluded family members</strong> — Someone expected to inherit but didn't</li>
    <li><strong>Late changes</strong> — Will changed close to death, raising capacity concerns</li>
    <li><strong>Blended families</strong> — Children from different relationships competing</li>
    <li><strong>Unclear intentions</strong> — Ambiguous wording or missing explanations</li>
    <li><strong>Undue influence</strong> — Suspicion that someone manipulated the will-maker</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to Prevent Will Disputes</h2>

  <p>While you can't guarantee your will won't be contested, you can significantly reduce the risk:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Get professional legal advice when drafting your will</li>
    <li>Document your reasons for your decisions</li>
    <li>Consider a statutory declaration confirming your capacity</li>
    <li>Communicate with family about your intentions</li>
    <li>Update your will after major life changes</li>
    <li>Consider whether a family provision claim is likely and plan accordingly</li>
  </ul>

